1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. e4
O-O 9. Bd3 a6 10. a4 Re8 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Re1 Nh5 13. Bg5 {This move is
supposed to cause some lack of harmony in Black's camp. For the plan based on .
..Ne5, the queen is best placed on the h4-d8 diagonal, while the next move
takes away from the h5-knight the natural retreat to f6.} Bf6 14. Be3 Ne5 15.
Be2 {The critical continuation, immediately putting the h5-knight under
pressure.} (15. Bf1 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Be5 17. g4 Ng7 (17... Nf4 18. Bxf4 Qf6 19.
Bxe5 Qxf3 20. Bg2 Qd3 21. Bxd6 $44) 18. Qg2 f5 19. f3 (19. exf5 gxf5 20. f4 Bd4
) 19... Bd7 (19... f4 $5 {looks tempting, but I was slightly worried about my
passive knight, as well as the possible transfer of the enemy knight to d3, in
order to undermine the blockade.}) 20. a5 Qf6 21. Rab1 Rab8 22. Nd1 fxe4 23.
fxe4 b5 (23... b6 $5) 24. b3 Re7 25. Bd3 Bd4 $15 {Borvander,T-Marin,M/Goteborg
rapid 2001 (0-1, 37)}) 15... Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Ng7 {At first sight, it may seem
that White has managed to force Black's kingside minor pieces to occupy rather
unfortunate squares. However, only two moves are needed (...Be5 and ...f5) in
order to make Black's position entirely viable. Later, the knight may move to
f5 and d4. Therefore, White has to hurry to open a new front on another area
of the board.} 17. Qd2 {Completing the development and defending the knight in
order to enable the opening of the queenside with a further b4.} ({Knowing
Gashimov's next move,} 17. a5 {certainly makes some sense.} Rb8 ({I would
prefer} 17... Bd7 $5 {, anticipating the knight's move to a4.} 18. Qd2 $140 b5
19. axb6 Qxb6 $132) 18. Na4 Bd7 19. Qd2 Bxa4 20. Rxa4 {Now, White was in time
to defend his b2-pawn.} Qd7 21. Rc4 $5 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (21. Ra2 b5 22. axb6 Rxb6
23. Rb1 Reb8 24. Be2 Qb7 $132 {[%cal Gg7e8,Ge8c7,Gc7b5,Gb5d4]}) 21... Qb5 (
21... b5 22. axb6 Rxb6 23. b4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gg7]}) 22. Rc2 b6 $6 (22... Be5 {
[%cal Gf7f5]} 23. Be2 $1) (22... Qa4 $5 {[%cal Gb7b5,Yb7b6]} 23. Bf4 Be5 {
[%cal Gf7f5]}) 23. Ra1 bxa5 24. Rxa5 Qb6 25. Ra2 $14 {Xu Jun (2535)-Chekhov,V 
(2525)/Beijing 1991/CBM 028 (1/2-1/2, 30). White has managed to defend his
b2-pawn safely, while the a6-pawn remains vulnerable. At the same time, the
g7-knight is still passive.}) 17... b6 {A multi-purpose move. Black prevents
a4-a5, which would make him lose flexibility on the queenside and enables the
rook's transfer to the kingside. I have commented on similar situations when ..
.b6 is useful in my last 3 articles about different variations of the Benoni.}
(17... Bd7 {1-0 Wang Yue (2689)-Cheparinov,I (2696)/Baku 2008/CBM 124/[Ftacnik]
(56)}) 18. Rab1 {[%cal Gb2b4]} (18. Be2 Bxc3 $5 19. bxc3 Rxe4 20. Bd3 Re8 21.
c4 {If White could set up the Q+B battery along the a1-h8 diagonal in time,
Black would be in trouble. However, the threat of rapid activation of the
knight via f5-d4 keeps Black in the game.} Bf5 22. Bf1 Bd7 {[%cal Gg7f5,Gf5d4]}
23. Bd3 (23. g4 $5 {[%csl Rg7]}) 23... Bf5 24. Bf1 Bd7 25. Bd3 {1/2-1/2
Onischuk,A (2664)-Gashimov,V (2679)/Dagomys 2008/CBM 124}) 18... Be5 {[%cal
Gf7f5]} 19. Bg5 ({Black's dymanic potential should not be underestimated. The
hurried} 19. b4 $6 {allows} Bxh3 $1 $132 20. gxh3 $2 Qf6 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Rf3]})
19... f6 $1 $146 {Since Black aims to play ...f5 anyway, this is not a
weakening move. Moreover, the pawn strengthens the control over the e5-square,
as will become clear a few moves later.} (19... Bf6 $6 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. b4 $14
{Savchenko,S (2563)-Cornette,M (2357)/Cappelle la Grande 2002/CBM 086 ext (0-1,
32)}) 20. Bf4 (20. Be3 f5 $132) 20... Ra7 21. b4 Rf7 $132 {White has managed
to open the queenside, but Black has regrouped most of his pieces in a
harmonious way. His only problem remains the activation of the knight, but
with so many "colleagues" around it, this should be solved in one way or
another.} 22. Bd1 {In most cases, after Bxe5 fxe5, the f3-bishop would be
hanging (...Bxh3 or ...Rxf3). Therefore, White removes it in advance, aiming
to activate it through a4.} ({White is not too well prepared for} 22. a5 {.
Black has several possible answers, the most ambitious (but also risky) being}
Bxf4 23. Qxf4 b5 24. bxc5 (24. Ne2 f5 {Here we can see why Black exchanged on
f4, to make the enemy queen occupy a vulnerable square.}) 24... Qxa5 $13) ({
The immediate intrusion with} 22. bxc5 bxc5 23. Rb8 {leads to sharp play after}
Bxf4 24. Qxf4 f5 25. Qd2 ({The tempting sacrifice} 25. Rxc8 Qxc8 26. Qxd6 {is
not too dangerous for Black after[%cal Ge4e5]} fxe4 27. Nxe4 Nf5 28. Nf6+ Rxf6
29. Rxe8+ Qxe8 30. Qxf6 Qe1+ 31. Kh2 Qxf2 32. Qxa6 Ne3 $11 {and perpetual
check cannot be avoided.}) 25... Rfe7 26. Qb2 Re5 27. Qb6 Qe7 $132) 22... Qc7 {
[%csl Gb8]} ({Benoni players usually refrain from moves such as} 22... c4 $5 {
, which release the tension and give up the control of the d4-square. However,
in this concrete case the plan based on the knight's transfer to c6 fails
because of Black's superior mobilization.} 23. Ne2 $6 Nh5 $1 24. Bh6 (24. Bxe5
fxe5 {would simply deny the knight's access to d4.}) 24... f5 $1 25. Nd4 fxe4
26. Bxh5 Qf6 $5) 23. bxc5 bxc5 24. Bxe5 fxe5 {The structure has changed,
becoming characteristic of the KI. Black's problem remains basically the same:
if he could only bring his knight to f4...} 25. Qg5 {AIming to keep Black's
kingside initiative under control.} ({Black has sufficient counterplay after
the more ambitious} 25. Rb2 {[%csl Ra5,Rb6,Rd6,Re5][%cal Gc3b1,Gb1a3,Ga3c4]}
Ref8 26. Qe3 Qe7 27. Nb1 Qh4 28. Na3 Rf6 29. Rf1 (29. Nc4 Nf5 $1 $132) 29... g5
30. Rb6 (30. Nc4 Nf5 31. exf5 Qxc4 32. Qxg5+ Kh8 $132 {[%csl Rd5,Rf5]}) 30...
g4 31. hxg4 Bxg4 32. Bxg4 (32. f3 $6 Nh5 $1 $40) 32... Qxg4 33. Nc4 Nh5 (33...
Rg6 34. g3 Nh5) 34. f3 Qg6 $132) 25... Ref8 26. Rb2 Rf4 27. Bg4 Qa5 (27... Bxg4
