Karjakin, Gashimov plays this move, although in slightly different
circumstances and with entirely different plans.} ({In the article published
in CBM 125, I examined the plan based on} 12... Qe7 {, when ...b6 is sometimes
useful at a slightly later stage.}) 13. Bf4 Qc7 14. Qd2 Bb7 {During the 50th
edition of the traditional Reggio Emilia tournament, I confessed to Vugar my
sincere admiration for his courage in playing the Benoni nowadays, as well as
for his ingeniosity and, not last, his excellent results. I remember him
mentioning the plan displayed in the present game and the name of Nakamura,
who once defended Black's point of view against strong opposition. Personally,
I have serious doubts about the merits of developing the bishop to b7. True,
the standard pawn break e5 is inhibited for a while, because it would leave
the d5-pawn weakened, but White can either prepare this break in a thorough
way or just switch to the alternate plan b4. In either case, the bishop is
doomed to passivity and so is Black. As a curiosity, I recently happened to
analyse a blocked position resulted from a hybrid between the KI and the BI. I
was shocked when one powerful engine suggested (in a rather normal position)
the manoeuvre ...Bd7-c8-b7-a8 as Black's second best line. Could it be that,
apart from providing doubtless help, computers tend to pervert our minds?!} 15.
